content.description:
Testing in Hobson follows the same principles as everything else in the system: tests are items, they run inside Hobson, and they use existing infrastructure rather than introducing special-cased machinery.

The key insight is that **nested instances already provide everything a test environment needs**: isolated storage (via ID prefixing), isolated DOM (via the iframe), and free cleanup (via cascade delete on instance deletion). Tests run inside a forked copy of the system, exercising real views, real rendering, and real storage — just in a disposable context.

This also supports a natural development workflow: fork into a nested instance, make changes, run tests against those changes, and promote the tested code back to the parent. The nested instance serves double duty as both sandbox and test environment.

## Design Principles

1. **Tests are items** — No external test harness. Test definitions, the assertion library, and the test runner are all regular items.
2. **Use existing infrastructure** — Nested instances for isolation, the rendering system for UI testing, the module system for loading test code, declarative watches for event-driven test scenarios.
3. **Test the real system** — Tests exercise live code inside a real Hobson environment, not mocks or simulations.
4. **Inspectable results** — Test outcomes are visible as rendered items, not hidden in a console log.
5. **No kernel changes** — Everything is implemented as user-space items.

## Workflow

### Development Testing

1. Create a `hobson-instance` item (the "test instance")
2. Import kernel + items into it (or it inherits them — see Promotion below)
3. Make code changes inside the nested instance
4. Run tests inside the nested instance
5. If tests pass, promote changed items back to parent
6. Delete the test instance (cascade cleanup removes all prefixed items)

### Regression Testing

Same as above, but skip step 3. Fork, run tests against unmodified code, verify nothing is broken.

## New Items Required

### 1. Test Assertion Library

**Item:** `test-lib` — **Type:** LIBRARY

Minimal assertion and test-grouping API. Each test file calls `createSuite()` to get its own isolated collector — no shared module-level state.

```javascript
const DEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 5000;

export function createSuite(name) {
  const results = [];

  function test(testName, fn) {
    const fullName = name ? `${name} > ${testName}` : testName;
    try {
      fn();
      results.push({ name: fullName, passed: true });
    } catch (e) {
      results.push({ name: fullName, passed: false, error: e.message });
    }
  }

  async function testAsync(testName, fn, timeout = DEFAULT_TIMEOUT) {
    const fullName = name ? `${name} > ${testName}` : testName;
    try {
      await Promise.race([
        fn(),
        new Promise((_, reject) =>
          setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`Timed out after ${timeout}ms`)), timeout)
        )
      ]);
      results.push({ name: fullName, passed: true });
    } catch (e) {
      results.push({ name: fullName, passed: false, error: e.message });
    }
  }

  function getResults() {
    return [...results];
  }

  return { test, testAsync, getResults };
}

export function assert(condition, message) {
  if (!condition) throw new Error(message || 'Assertion failed');
}

export function assertEquals(actual, expected, message) {
  if (actual !== expected) {
    throw new Error(message || `Expected ${JSON.stringify(expected)}, got ${JSON.stringify(actual)}`);
  }
}

// Note: comparison via JSON.stringify — key order matters and undefined values are dropped.
export function assertDeepEquals(actual, expected, message) {
  if (JSON.stringify(actual) !== JSON.stringify(expected)) {
    throw new Error(message || `Expected ${JSON.stringify(expected)}, got ${JSON.stringify(actual)}`);
  }
}
```

This is intentionally minimal. Users can extend or replace it.

### 2. Test Runner View

**Item:** `test-runner-view` — **Type:** VIEW — **For type:** `test-suite` (see below)

Discovers and runs test items, displays results. The test runner view:

- Queries for all items tagged with a `test` tag
- Loads each test item via `require()`
- Calls its exported `run(api)` function, passing the standard renderer API
- Collects results
- Renders a pass/fail summary with expandable failure details

The view provides a "Run All" button and optionally individual "Run" buttons per test item. Results display inline: green for pass, red for fail with error message.

### 3. Test Suite Type

**Item:** `test-suite` (TYPE_DEFINITION)

A container item that the test runner view renders for. Creating one and navigating to it gives you the test runner UI. Content is minimal — possibly just a `name` and optional `description`. The test runner view does the real work.

### 4. Example Test Items

Test items are CODE or LIBRARY items tagged with `test` that export a `run` function:

```javascript
// Example: note-view-tests
import { createSuite, assert, assertEquals } from 'test-lib';

export async function run(api) {
  const { test, testAsync, getResults } = createSuite('Note View');

  // Data layer tests
  await testAsync('creates a note with correct structure', async () => {
    const note = await api.set({
      id: crypto.randomUUID(),
      type: 'note-type-id',
      content: { title: 'Test Note', body: 'Hello world' }
    });
    assert(note.id, 'Note should have an ID');
    assertEquals(note.content.title, 'Test Note');
  });

  // Rendering tests — navigate to the item and query the iframe DOM directly
  await testAsync('renders title in an h1', async () => {
    const note = await api.set({
      id: crypto.randomUUID(),
      type: 'note-type-id',
      content: { title: 'My Title', body: 'Content here' }
    });
    // Tests run inside a nested instance — the whole iframe is ours.
    // Navigate to the note, then query the DOM.
    await api.navigate(note.id);
    const h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
    assert(h1, 'Should render an h1');
    assertEquals(h1.textContent, 'My Title');
  });

  return getResults();
}
```

Since tests run inside a nested instance, the items they create via `api.set()` are automatically prefixed and isolated. No cleanup code needed. Rendering tests use the instance's own DOM — no special rendering API required.

## Promotion Mechanism

After tests pass in a nested instance, changed items need to return to the parent. This requires a small library and optionally a view.

### Promotion Library

**Item:** `instance-promote` — **Type:** LIBRARY

The parent can already see child items via `getAllRaw()` — they're in the same IndexedDB, just prefixed. Promotion is:

1. Read all items from the child instance (prefixed)
2. Compare against parent items (by unprefixed ID) to find what changed
3. Present a diff for review
4. On confirmation, write the changed items to parent storage (stripping prefix)

```javascript
export async function getChangedItems(instanceId, api) {
  const allRaw = await api.getAllRaw();
  const prefix = instanceId + ':';
  const childItems = allRaw
    .filter(i => i.id.startsWith(prefix))
    .map(i => ({ ...i, id: i.id.slice(prefix.length) }));

  const changes = [];
  for (const child of childItems) {
    const parent = await api.get(child.id).catch(() => null);
    if (!parent) {
      changes.push({ type: 'new', item: child });
    } else if (child.modified > parent.modified) {
      changes.push({ type: 'modified', item: child, parent });
    }
  }
  return changes;
}

export async function promote(items, api) {
  for (const item of items) {
    await api.set(item);
  }
}
```

### Promotion View (optional)

A view for `hobson-instance` items (or a separate tool) that shows a list of changed items with diffs. Each change has a checkbox; a "Promote Selected" button applies them. This makes the critical promotion step visible and reversible.

## What This Does Not Include

- **Mocking** — Tests run against real storage, real rendering, real code. If a test needs to isolate a single function, it can call it directly. No mock framework.
- **Coverage tracking** — Out of scope. The system has no bytecode instrumentation. Manual coverage is sufficient at this scale.
- **CI/CD integration** — Hobson is offline-first and browser-based. Tests are run by the user, inside the system, when they choose to.
- **Snapshot testing** — Comparing DOM snapshots across runs. Could be added later as a library item if useful, but not in the initial implementation.

## Implementation Order

1. **test-lib** — The assertion library. No dependencies, immediately usable from the REPL.
2. **test-suite type** — Trivial type definition.
3. **test-runner-view** — View for the test suite type. Discovers and runs tests, shows results.
4. **Example test items** — A few tests for existing functionality (notes, type chain validation, view lookup) to validate the approach.
5. **instance-promote library** — Promotion mechanism.
6. **Promotion view** — UI for reviewing and applying changes (optional, can use REPL initially).

Steps 1–4 are the core. Steps 5–6 complete the workflow but could follow later.
